comments.body: done.

Some preliminary considerations to discuss with DACS and Alma teams:
1. Alma currently only has item records for SC ReCAP collections, not for everything.
2. We are currently not sending items as part of the nightly aspace2alma. 
3. To automate this process, we would need to modify the nightly process to include items. Question: would we want to *only* include the ReCAP locations? Probably.
4. Because Alma doesn't reject duplicate barcodes that come in as part of an import job, we need to front-load a deduplication process. (Let's triple-check this. It is too stupid to be true.)
5. The silver lining is that everything that is going to ReCAP must be barcoded, so the deduplication can safely be done on barcode, even if Alma doesn't do it for us.
6. As @mzelesky suggests, we could run an export job for SC items in ReCAP locations that gets uploaded to lib-sftp. Question: what would be the failsafe in case the items export job or upload to lib-sftp fails? (An outdated file on lib-sftp would result in a duplicate items upload to Alma because it would not reflect items that have been imported to Alma in the meantime.) We need some sort of "burn after reading" mechanism.
7. The aspace2alma job would then have to grab the file from there first, dedupe on barcode, and send back to lib-sftp only the items not found in Alma. Failsafe could be that it doesn't find a file, it exits.
9. On the Alma end, we need to set the (currently manual) import job to run on a schedule

Concerns (notes from meeting with @mzelesky ):
1. will barcodes change before sending to ReCAP?
2. Stakeholders should meet with Marie to make sure that isn't the case
3. We will use a publishing profile to get item information from Alma
4. We will use an import profile to import data to Alma
5. Preprocessing could involve looking at the published report
6. For matches that are found, we may need to keep track of the item id
7. failsafe: when processed, rename the file
8. should this really be nightly? or weekly? the publishing job runs for 4 hours
9. how will this project fit into the ReCAPping quotas?

@mzelesky has created a draft publishing job in the Sandbox.

Items to possibly tweak include
- [ ] MARC fields
- [ ] a subdirectory within aspace
- [ ] do we need to keep track of identifiers in the end?

(there may be more)

bibdata.title: 650 Indigenous Languages aren't always adding the correct facet

comments.body:
Moved this a bug issue: https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/issues/2187

I did find some odd cases where bibs should be tagged as "Indigenous Languages (Western Hemisphere)" but are not. 

First, it looks as though **$v Texts** is not working properly.

Among the results of [Algonquian languages—Texts](https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/?f[subject_facet][]=Algonquian+languages%E2%80%94Texts) (19)
[6 records](https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog?utf8=%E2%9C%93&f%5Bsubject_facet%5D%5B%5D=Algonquian+languages%E2%80%94Texts&f1=all_fields&q1=&op2=NOT&f2=all_fields&q2=%22Indigenous+Languages+%28Western+Hemisphere%29%22&op3=AND&f3=title&q3=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bbegin%5D=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bend%5D=&sort=score+desc%2C+pub_date_start_sort+desc%2C+title_sort+asc&search_field=advanced&commit=Search
) are not tagged

None of [Apache languages—Texts](https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/?f[subject_facet][]=Apache+languages%E2%80%94Texts) (3) is tagged.

Among the results of [Zapotec language—Texts](https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/?f[subject_facet][]=Zapotec+language%E2%80%94Texts) (42)
[7 records](https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog?utf8=%E2%9C%93&f%5Bsubject_facet%5D%5B%5D=Zapotec+language%E2%80%94Texts&f1=all_fields&q1=&op2=NOT&f2=all_fields&q2=%22Indigenous+Languages+%28Western+Hemisphere%29%22&op3=AND&f3=title&q3=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bbegin%5D=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bend%5D=&sort=score+desc%2C+pub_date_start_sort+desc%2C+title_sort+asc&search_field=advanced&commit=Search) are not tagged

Now I know Blacklight does not distinguish between $v Texts and $x Texts, and for our tagging interest we are only interested in the former, but spot-checking found plenty of $v Texts in there.

Or take a look at the title [_Bitter water: Diné oral histories of the Navajo-Hopi land dispute_](https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog?utf8=%E2%9C%93&sort=score+desc%2C+pub_date_start_sort+desc%2C+title_sort+asc&f1=all_fields&f3=title&op3=AND&q1=&q3=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bbegin%5D=&range%5Bpub_date_start_sort%5D%5Bend%5D=&search_field=left_anchor&q=Bitter+water+Dine%CC%81) (4 records)
All four have the identical string 650 #0 a| Navajo language v| Texts.
But only the three with **041 a| nav** are tagged. (One of them is a Harvard copy. I visited [hollis.harvard.edu](https://hollis.harvard.edu/primo-explore/sourceRecord?vid=HVD2&docId=01HVD_ALMA212143122110003941) to find its source marc record)
MMSID [99125348431306421](https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog?utf8=%E2%9C%93&search_field=all_fields&q=99125348431306421) has **041 a| eng** only, and is not tagged as Indigenous Languages.

Second, my analysis also exposes some encoding errors in the 041 fields of bib records. Lumped constructions like

- 041 $a algeng
- 041 $a engspanah

may be found in older records (and I suspect a higher presence in SCSB records), and would be skipped by the tagging project. 
Would it be possible to loosen up the matching criteria a tiny bit to scoop up such records as well?

pulfalight.title: Add location information to each item in the Request Cart

comments.body:
For Firestone and Mudd let's link to this - https://library.princeton.edu/special-collections/visit-us
Engineering - https://library.princeton.edu/engineering
PPL - honestly I am feeling a bit dumb because I can't figure out where we should be directing people.
RECAP And Annex B - @faithc do you have a suggestion for this? Both are physical locations that cannot be accessed. Maybe those just don't have a link?

I don't think Plasma Physics is a repo/location. It seems that collections related to plasma physics are part of UA or Engineering. 

Another repo/location is the East Asian Library. It looks like the lone collection associated with that repository, EA01, is at ReCAP. 

Are there collections at Annex B? 

It also makes sense to me for ReCAP and Annex B to not have a link. Can the location name for both be something like "Offsite storage facility"?

Do we think links in general are necessary here?

I think links for Firestone and Mudd are useful. I also think keeping the names of Annex and Recap are helpful for staff but just not a link.
Are EA items circulated at firestone then keeping that not a link makes sence to me.

I'm not sure if EA01 would be viewed at Firestone, but I think associating it with that location for now should be sufficient. Should this also then get the https://library.princeton.edu/special-collections/visit-us link?
I think that is the safest option. I have also just added a link on that page to the ask us form so people can get to us if needed

I'm hearing:

Firestone Library -  https://library.princeton.edu/special-collections/visit-us
Mudd Manuscript Library - https://library.princeton.edu/special-collections/visit-us
ReCAP - No Link
Annex B - No Link
Engineering Library - https://library.princeton.edu/special-collections/visit-us
PPPL - No link, and probably won't show up anywhere.

RIght?

So it's either visit special collections or nothing.

Engineering should be https://library.princeton.edu/engineering.
EA should be https://library.princeton.edu/special-collections/visit-us (for now).
